            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ajay Parsa is a product of the Bay Area\u2019s quiet, suburban ambition. The only child of Indian immigrants who settled in Fremont in the 1970s, he was raised in a home that valued education and civic duty. His father, a civil engineer, designed water systems, while his mother was a beloved public librarian. While his father hoped he\u2019d follow a path into engineering, Ajay was always more fascinated by the human systems that governed cities, spending hours in his mother's library reading about urban planning and political history.\n\nThis passion led him to UC Berkeley for a degree in Public Policy. The true turning point, however, came during an undergraduate internship in a city supervisor's office. He was tasked with analyzing constituent complaints about a bus line, and in the dry data, he saw a story of struggle: service workers late for jobs, elderly residents isolated from appointments. He saw public transportation not as a logistical problem, but as the city\u2019s circulatory system, essential for equity and opportunity.\n\nAfter graduation, he began his steady, methodical climb through San Francisco\u2019s public administration, landing at the SFMTA. For over two decades, he has been a constant force, a repository of institutional memory as mayors and tech booms have come and go. His dedication, however, strained his marriage, leading to an amicable divorce a decade ago; his ex-wife, a corporate lawyer, couldn\u2019t reconcile her fast-paced world with his unwavering belief in the slow, grinding work of public service.\n\nToday, Ajay lives in a modest one-bedroom apartment in Hayes Valley. His daily 1.8-mile commute on the 21-Hayes bus is both a routine and a field study; he knows the drivers by name and feels every lurch and delay personally. Evenings are for policy briefs and phone calls, but weekends are fiercely guarded for his teenage daughter, Maya, who lives with her mother in Marin. They explore the city together, from dim sum in the Richmond to grabbing coffee in the Mission.\n\nAjay\u2019s dream isn\u2019t for wealth or recognition, but for a fully-funded, seamlessly integrated transit system that works for everyone. He envisions a future San Francisco where a car is an inconvenience, not a necessity. His greatest hope is that he can help build a city that is as easy for Maya to navigate as it is for the powerful and privileged."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten, sitting cross-legged on the floor of the Fremont library, the air smelling of old paper and his mother\u2019s rosewater perfume. She brought him a heavy, forgotten book about San Francisco\u2019s old streetcar network. Tracing the ghost-lines on the faded map with his finger, he didn't see engineering; he saw veins and arteries. In that quiet moment, his father\u2019s world of concrete pipes transformed into a living system of human connection, a revelation that set the course for his entire life.\n\n2.\nHe can still feel the weight of the single sheet of paper from his Berkeley internship. It was a complaint letter, handwritten in shaky cursive by a woman in the Bayview, detailing how she\u2019d missed a dialysis appointment due to a late T-Third train. The dry data on his spreadsheet suddenly had a face and a consequence. A hot, quiet anger settled in his chest\u2014a protective fury that became the moral engine for his career. Public transit wasn't a service; it was a lifeline.\n\n3.\nThe conversation that ended his marriage wasn't a fight. They sat on their balcony overlooking the city, and she said, with a lawyer\u2019s sad precision, \"Ajay, you're married to a system that will never love you back.\" He knew she was right, in a way. But she couldn't see the faces\u2014the nurses, students, and cooks he saw on his commute. He was choosing them over a world of billable hours. It was a quiet, profound heartbreak, a sacrifice he felt was necessary for the city he served.\n\n4.\nIt was 5:30 AM on a Tuesday seven years ago. He stood on a corner in the Excelsior District, a cold wind whipping off the street, just to watch the first run of a new crosstown route he\u2019d championed for two years. As the bus hissed to a stop and a handful of hospital workers boarded, a deep, bone-weary satisfaction settled over him. There was no ceremony, no recognition. Just a bus, arriving on time. In the grinding machinery of bureaucracy, this small, tangible success felt like a monumental victory.\n\n5.\nLast year, riding the 38-Geary with Maya, she pressed her face to the window, watching the city blur by. \"This bus is like a time machine,\" she said. \"You see all the different parts of the city at once.\" Hearing his life's obsession articulated so simply by his teenage daughter filled him with a fierce hope. It wasn't about funding or policy briefs. It was about giving her, and every kid like her, the keys to this complex, beautiful city, one bus ride at a time."
